https://leetcode.com/problems/binary-tree-maximum-path-sum/description/

Question:
Input: root = [-10,9,20,null,null,15,7]
Output: 42
Explanation: The optimal path is 15 -> 20 -> 7 with a path sum of 15 + 20 + 7 = 42.

SOLUTION:
OPTIMAL:
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(h)

/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    int ans=Integer.MIN_VALUE;
    public int maxPathSum(TreeNode root) {
        helper(root);
        return ans;
    }
    public int helper(TreeNode root){
        if(root==null)return 0;
        int left=Math.max(helper(root.left),0);
        int right=Math.max(helper(root.right),0);
        int path=root.val+left+right;
        ans=Math.max(ans,path);
        return root.val+Math.max(left,right);
    }
}


Step 1 to Step 4 (Complete Flow Until Node 20)
🔹 Step 1: Visit Node 9

Left child = null → return 0

Right child = null → return 0

So:

left = 0
right = 0
pathSum = 9 + 0 + 0 = 9

Update global:

ans = 9

Return to parent:

return 9
🔹 Step 2: Visit Node 15

Left = 0

Right = 0

pathSum = 15
ans = max(9,15) = 15

Return:

15
🔹 Step 3: Visit Node 7

Left = 0

Right = 0

pathSum = 7
ans = 15

Return:

7
🔹 Step 4: Visit Node 20

Now we have values from children:

left = 15
right = 7

Compute full path through 20:

pathSum = 20 + 15 + 7 = 42

Update global:

ans = max(15,42) = 42

Now IMPORTANT:

We cannot return 42 to parent
because that path splits into two directions.

So we return only one side:

return 20 + max(15,7)
= 20 + 15
= 35

At this point:

ans = 42

And 35 goes upward to -10.
